WORLD CORPORATE INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

INTERNATIONAL STANDARDS/AMERICAN INDEMNITY

As a first step in a planned expansion into the insurance sector
International Standards Group Ltd (ISG) has announced plans to acquire
American Indemnity Co, Galveston TX.  American Indemnity has annual
revenues of US$100m.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "17"></A>Copyright
WORLD CORPORATE INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

KANSA

Former managers of the bankrupt Kansa Pension Insurance Co. Ltd (Elake-
Kansa), Helsinki, were served with writs for damages towards the end of
December, the last possible moment before the statute of limitations
took effect (WICR159/24).  The suits, covering events in 1992, sought
an estimated FM240m (US$55.2m).  Liquidators are suing, among other
things, over property deals which were allegedly sometimes approved by
the boards in retrospect, and sometimes with not all board members
present at crucial meetings.  Further suits could follow concerning
events in 1993 and 1994, and these could raise the claims to FM1bn.
One matter awaiting clarification is the disappearance of FM700m in the
summer of 1993, without the authorisation of the board.

Seven of the Kansa companies have been the subject of extraordinary
audits and all of them are nearly complete.  The administrators have
asked some of the larger creditors for comments, which are expected
this month, but should not change the assessment of management's
responsibilities.  The auditors' reports have also been submitted to
the insurance department of the ministry of social affairs and health.

The bankrupt companies are Elake-Kansa, Kansa Life Insurance Co Ltd
(Henki-Kansa), Helsinki, two reinsurers, Kansa International Corp,
Kansy-yhtyma, and Finansipalveluosakeyhtio Kansa.  The pension company
is in the worst financial condition, with non-guaranteed credits, and a
deficit of around FM1bn (WICR159/24).  The situation of Henki-Kansa
appears better, but depends heavily on the outcome of the legal action.
 Indeed, the state of both companies will only be clear when the legal
actions have been settled, and decided which assets belong to which
company.  The general aim is to reduce the deficits of the bankrupt
companies through selling the Kansa Group's US-based subsidiary
Clarendon Group.  According to Mr Jaatinen the sale is progressing, and
should be finalised during 1996.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "18"></A>Copyright
WORLD CORPORATE INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

LIMIT

London Insurance Market Investment Trust plc (LIMIT), London, has
increased its capacity allocated to the Lloyd's market by 5.2% to
#610.25m (US$946m) for 1996.  The increase means that LIMIT now writes
6.5% of Lloyd's total capacity.  LIMIT said that it will be providing
capacity to two syndicates which it has not previously supported,
#0.25m going to non-marine (mainly nuclear risks) syndicate 1176 (Cox
Newton & Harman Ltd) and #3m to syndicate 1206 managed by Owen & Wilby
Underwriting Agency Ltd, a new managing agent for 1996 formed to manage
the syndicate which will be similar to that of syndicate 718 in the
sphere of accident & health risks, with the exception that no London
market reinsurance risks will be written.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "19"></A>Copyright
WORLD CORPORATE INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

LUI

Creditors of KWELM subsidiaries of London United Investments plc,
London (Kingscroft Insurance Co Ltd, Walbrook Insurance Co Ltd, El Paso
Insurance Co Ltd, Lime Street Insurance Co Ltd, Mutual Reinsurance Co
Ltd) received a second payment of US$140m at the beginning of January
(WICR170/23).  To date scheme administrators at Coopers & Lybrand have
set aside a total of $703m for creditors, and have been able to
increase the initial payment percentages set for all five units thanks
to improved reinsurance collection.  Kingscroft creditors received
payments increased by 2 percentage points to 10%, Walbrook from 4% to
5%, El Paso from 8% to 10%, Lime Street from 9% to 11%, and Mutual from
5% to 6%.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "20"></A>Copyright
WORLD CORPORATE INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

NATIONAL (CALCUTTA)

National Insurance Co Ltd, Calcutta, introduced India's first package
insurance policy for farmers in West Bengal on 25 November.  Union
Minister of State for Finance, Dr Debiprosad Pad, described the scheme
as a significant milestone and urged the other insurance companies to
introduce similar policies.  The scheme will be extended to other areas
if it proves successful in West Bengal.  The package covers 12 frequent
hazards in rural areas, including fire and allied, burglary, electronic
equipment such as TVs and VCRs, bicycles, livestock, poultry and
handcarts.  The fire and burglary sections are compulsory, with an
annual premium of Rs152.50.  Taking five or more sections generates a
premium discount of 15% to 20%.



