<A NAME = "25"></A>Copyright
WORLD INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

IN THE COURTS

On 21 December, Mr Justice Gatehouse found "with considerable
hesitation" that no competent members' agent could have placed names on
Feltrim syndicate 540/2 in 1990 (although some categories of names
failed to demonstrate their case), and "with more confidence" that the
names case failed with regard to syndicate 847.

On the same day, the Court of Appeal upheld the "pay now, sue later"
ruling by Mr Justice Rix in Marchant & Eliot Ltd v Higgins (WIR524/9).
Lloyd's served approximately 300 writs on recalcitrant names the same
day.

On 6 December, Lloyd's was also successful in a High Court action, also
heard by Mr Justice Gatehouse, in which Diana Aldrich sought to prevent
drawdown on her Lloyd's deposit because she claimed to have been
fundamentally mistaken about the nature of Lloyd's when she became a
name.  The case was summarily dismissed.

On 3 January, the Colorado Court of Appeal partially reversed a Denver
District Court preventing drawdown on Colorado names' deposits in an
action initiated by the state securities commissioner.  Meanwhile, an
outline settlement with the 700-odd members of the American Names
Association has been agreed in principle by Lloyd's.

As a result of the decision of Mr Justice Cresswell in Henderson et al
v Merrett Syndicates Ltd et al (WIR524/1), E&O insurers served the
victorious Pulbrook 334 (1985) names with a notice of intention to
avoid payment (WIR506/1).  The names have begun liquidation proceedings
against Pulbrook U/W management Ltd, London.

The appeal by the Gooda Walker Action Group on the issue of the
taxation of awards will be heard by the House of Lords on 16 January.



