<A NAME = "35"></A>Copyright
WORLD INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

MARINE

14.12.95, marine, sinking, fatalities

Indonesia:  passenger vessel `Bunga Coklat 1', en route from Kolaka
district for Wajo district, South Sulawesi province, swamped in heavy
seas while crossing the Gulf of Bone, app 950 miles NE Jakarta.  At
least 15 dead.

22.12.95, marine, sinking, fatalities

Philippines:  coast-to-coast vessel `Watari Abe', capsized nr Calauag
coast, 150 miles S Manila.  At least 10 dead.

25.12.95, marine, sinking, fatalities

Indonesia:  mv `Andhika Wanasatya', Indonesian registered, 3,890 gt,
built 1977, en route from Papua New Guinea for Hong Kong, sank W of
Luzon Island, South China Sea.  1 dead, 12 missing, feared dead.

29.12.95, marine, sinking, fatalities

Norway:  m stern trawler `Novgorodets', Russian registered, sank app 20
miles off Tronds province, Arctic Norway.  1 dead, 9 missing, feared
dead.

5.1.96, marine, capsize

Indonesia:  mv `Bianka Prima', Indonesian registered, en route from
Pontianak, East Kalimantan for Sunda Kelapa, sank in bad weather,
Karimata Straits, app 186 miles N Jakarta.  9 missing.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "36"></A>Copyright
WORLD INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

ROAD/RAIL

16.12.95, road, accident, fatalities

UK:  mechanical digger being transported on top of lorry on minor road,
between Castle-an-Dinas, nr St Columb Major, Cornwall.  Chain holding
arm of digger broke causing arm to swing round and strike several cars
on opposite side of road.  5 dead, 5 injured.

18.12.95, road, collision, fatalities

Brazil:  bus and tanker truck, in collision, causing fuel load to
explode, Sao Paulo.  At least 22 dead.

21.12.95, rail, crash, fatalities

Egypt:  train, en route from Cairo for Bani Suef, ran into back of
another train in thick fog, Badrasheen, 28km S Cairo.  At least 75
dead, 76 injured.

23.12.95, road, accident, fatalities

Turkey:  bus plunged off bridge into ravine, Taurus mountains, nr
Ulukisla.  15 dead, 26 injured.

1.1.96, road, collision, fatalities

Pakistan:  bus, en route for Sargodha crashed into back of stationary
wagon, nr Chani Muhammad Qazi.  16 dead, 15 injured.

2.1.96, road, accident, fatalities

Zaire:  bus, converted from a lorry, plunged into ravine outside
Kinshasa.  72 dead.

3.1.96, road, collision, fatalities

Mexico:  two buses in head-on collision, desert highway nr US border,
Sonoita, app 175 miles E Tijuana, Sonora state.  Suspected cause: one
of drivers fell asleep.  At least 25 dead, 27 injured.

9.1.96, rail, collision, fatalities

Bangladesh:  local train, en route from Chittagong for Chandpur, and
Sagarika Express train, en route for Chittagong, in collision causing
derailment of both locomotives and four carriages, Kongaish, nr
Chandpur, app 110kms E Dhaka.  At least 16 dead, app 200 injured.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "37"></A>Copyright
WORLD INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

AVIATION

4.11.93, aviation, crash, further report

Hong Kong:  re Boeing 747-409 (B-165), operator China Airlines Ltd,
flight CAL605, en route from Taipei for Hong Kong, overshot runway on
landing at Kai Tak airport in poor visibility caused by gusty winds and
heavy rain (tropical storm `Ira'), plunged into Hong Kong harbour, app
1139 local (WIR475/12).  (9.1) Accident due to pilot error, according
to report.  Pilot inadvertently advanced aircraft's thrust levers
instead of reverse thrust on landing at Kai Tak.

10.8.95, aviation, crash, fatalities, further report

San Salvador:  re Boeing 737-2H6, owned and operated by Aerolineas de
Guatemala (Aviateca Guatemala), flight no 901, en route from Miami FL
for San Jose, Costa Rica, crashed in bad weather, nr Chichotepec
volcano, app 38 miles from San Salvador, after 2000 local (WIR519/13).
(28.12.95) Damage to electrical navigation system by lightning, was
"direct cause" of the accident, according to government official.

14.12.95, aviation, crash, fatalities

Italy:  twin-prop Antonov 24, owned by Romavia Air Co, operator Banat
Air Transport Co, en route from Verona for Bucharest via Timisoara,
plunged to the ground from altitude of 150 metres and crashed minutes
after take-off from Verona, app 1954 GMT.  49 dead.

19.12.95, aviation, crash, fatalities

Angola:  Lockheed Electra, owned by Trans Service Airlift (TSA), on
charter to Jonas Savimbi's opposition UNITA movement, en route from
Kinshasa, crashed at Kahengula, Lunda Norte province.  Up to 141 dead.

20.12.95, aviation, crash, fatalities

Colombia:  Boeing 757-200, operator American Airlines, flight no 965,
en route from Miami for Cali, reported engine trouble, app 2145 EST,
then crashed a few minutes later into San Jose mountain, nr Buga, app
35 miles NE Cali.  Risk broked by Alexander & Alexander and Alexander
Howden Aviation.  Hull valued at just over US$50m.  163 dead, at least
8 survived.

8.1.96, aviation, crash, fatalities

Zaire:  Antonov 32 cargo aircraft, Russian-built, reported owned by
African Air, en route from Ndolo airport, failed to gain height on take-
off and ploughed app 100 metres through market, engulfing it in flames,
Kinshasa, app 1300 local.  At least 297 dead.  (10.1) According to
Transport Minister, aircraft was at least 595lb overweight.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "38"></A>Copyright
WORLD INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

LIABILITY, AWARDS, SETTLEMENTS

13.12.95, road accident, award

UK:  Andrew Collins, left a spastic quadriplegic in accident with a
private ambulance, awarded #1.1m (US$1.7m).

14.12.95, rape claims, settlement

US:  hospital in Inverness FL, to pay #3.2m (US$4.9m) to 40 women who
claimed a former nurse raped or molested them in the recovery room
after they had surgery.

19.12.95, road accident, award

US:  federal court, Hammond IN, (jury) awarded C$8m (US$5.9m) to John
Paul Miksis who suffered brain injuries when he was hit by a Schneider
National Carriers Inc truck, against Schneider National Carriers.

8.1.96, Gulf War victims, award

Sri Lanka:  United Nations Compensation Commission awarded Rs3.8bn
(US$76m) to 18,155 Sri Lankan migrant workers and their families for
loss of lives, property and wages during the Gulf War of 1990-1991.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "39"></A>Copyright
WORLD INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

NATURAL CATASTROPHES

12.12.95, bad weather, property damage, fatalities, further report

US:  re hurricane-force winds and heavy rain flooded roads, uprooted
trees, cut electricity and telephone services, damaged property,
northern CA and OR (WIR527/13).  (?.12) Personal Insurance Federation
of California (PIFC) ests insured losses of at least US$250m.  (15.12)
State Farm, Bloomington IL, has received 25,000 claims, est cost less
than US$40m.  (22.12) PCS-AISG ests insured damage at US$240m.

13.12.95, bad weather, property damage

Iran:  flooding and heavy snow cut off 00's villages, central and
southern Iran.  Floods caused damage est at Rials5.2bn (US$1.7bn),
Bushehr province.  Damage to farmland, roads and power installations
est at Rials12.7bn (US$4.2m), Hormuzgan province.

14.12.95, bad weather, property damage, fatalities

Brazil:  record rainfall flooded homes, led to landslides, Minas Gerais
state.  16 dead.

15.12.95, bad weather, property damage, fatalities

Philippines:  heavy rainfall led to flash floods, Davao City, 600 miles
S Manila.  Parts of city under five feet of water.  9 dead, 3 missing.

19.12.95, bad weather, property damage, fatalities

South Africa:  torrential rain led to flooding, Eastern Transvaal.  At
least 6 dead.

19.12.95, earthquake, property damage, fatalities

Guatemala:  earthquake, measuring Richter 5.3, lasting nine seconds,
epicentre app 50 miles N Guatemala City, struck app 1456 local.
Several houses damaged and road destroyed.  1 dead, at least 1 injured.

20.12.95, earthquake, fatalities

Indonesia:  earthquake, measuring Richter 5.5, epicentre 110km NE
Wamena, struck app 0823 local, causing landslides in at least 10
villages, Kurima sub-district.  4 dead.

25.12.95, bad weather, property damage

Jamaica:  overnight showers led to flooding, Ocho Rios, St Ann.  Motor
vehicles swept away, homes flooded, cables and underground pipes
uprooted, road surfaces eroded.  Preliminary est damage: US$50m.

23.12.95, bad weather, property damage

UK:  blizzards and winds up to 100mph damaged power lines, blocking
roads, northern Scotland (see story p?).  Power supplies cut to 000's
of homes, Scotland, and all roads closed on Shetland Islands.  Drifts
up to 30-ft high, transport disrupted.  Shetland Islands declared state
of emergency.

27.12.95, bad weather, property damage, fatalities

Philippines:  heavy rains triggered flooding and landslides, Cagayan,
Isabela, Quirino, Nueva Vizcaya and Aurora provinces.  Some 442 houses
damaged or destroyed.  Est damage to crops and infrastructure put at
Pesos13m (US$500,000).  President declared Aurora under state of
calamity and released Pesos1m (US$38,461) in aid.  At least 13 dead, 3
missing.

27.12.95, bad weather, property damage

Albania:  heavy rain led to widespread flooding, north-western areas.
More than 5,000 hectares land submerged, 00's of houses destroyed,
Snkodra, Malesi e Madhe, Lezhe and Kruja districts.

27.12.95, bad weather, flooding, fatalities

South Africa:  heavy seasonal rains caused R Umsunduzi and Slangspruit
tributary to burst their banks, causing flash floods, Pietermaritzburg
and surrounding region, KwaZulu-Natal province.  At least 166 dead.
(28.12) National disaster area declared.  Central govt to match R1m
(US$278,000) in aid granted by provincial administration.

30.12.95, bad weather, fatalities

Brazil:  heavy rainstorms led to floods and landslides, southern and
east-central areas.  App 1,000 homes washed away plus bridges and
stretches of highway, Santa Catarina state  At least 61 dead, 31
missing.

1.1.96, earthquake, fatalities

Indonesia:  earthquake, measuring Richter 7, epicentre Celebes Sea, app
125km N Palu, Sulawesi island, triggered tidal waves of 1.5 metres.  At
least 384 wooden houses and government buildings damaged.  Earthquake
led to tidal wave, Sulawest island, left 8 dead, flooding, Sumatera,
left 16 dead.

3.1.96, bad weather, property damage, fatalities

Indonesia:  several days of rain triggered flooding, northern Aceh
province, Sumatra.  Up to 190 villages, rice fields, palm plantations
and coffee growing areas flooded, 000's made homeless, Rantau oil field
shut down.  At least 18 dead, 9 missing.  Est losses, including
livestock, Aceh Province, put at US$87m.  (6.1) flooding spread to
western part of Java island, destroying app 2,871 hectares of paddy
fields and affecting more than 4,000 houses and schools in 13 villages.
 (9.1) heavy rains caused R Ciliwung to overflow, flooding tens of
thousands of homes, central, east and south Jakarta.  At least 11 dead.

3.1.96, bad weather, property damage

US:  tornado, accompanying thunderstorm, damaged 100 homes, overturned
cars and left app 20,000 homes without electricity, Dade County, app 12
miles S Miami FL, app 0810 local.

4.1.96, bad weather, property damage, fatalities

CIS:  Kazakhstan:  two weeks of blizzards caused est damage of
Tenge200m (US$3m).  Electricity and telephone lines, several buildings
damaged.  113 dead, 5 missing.

4.1.96, bad weather, property damage

Romania:  melting snow and rain flooded 25 districts, washed away app
4,000 houses, north-western areas.  Est damage put at more than Lei10bn
(US$3.4m).

7.1.96, snowstorm, fatalities

US:  snowstorm, "largest in at least two years", swept across eastern
US, leading to closure of airports in Washington, Boston, New York, and
Philadelphia, businesses and schools.  000's flights cancelled.  Up to
24 inches of snow fell, Washington DC, with winds gusting up to 40mph.
App 30 inches of snow fell, Philadelphia area.  State of emergency
declared, New York and Boston, plus at least eight north-eastern
states.  Up to 20-30 inches snow fell, Appalachian mountains, West
Virginia.  App 80 dead.  Airlines expect blizzard costs to run into
"millions of dollars".  (9.1) Pennsylvania governor est costs to state
businesses at "hundreds of millions of dollars" and cost to area state
and local government "in the millions".  (10.1)  Economic damage est at
between US$5bn and US$10bn.



