<A NAME = "17"></A>Copyright
ASIAN ECONOMIC NEWS via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Philippines to cut tariffs on 155 products in '96+

MANILA, Dec. 26 Kyodo

     The Philippines will lower import tariffs on some 155 products
next year as part of an accelerated program to create a free trade
market in Southeast Asia by 2003, Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) documents said Tuesday.
     According to the documents, the 155 items are among 717 products
in Manila's temporary exclusion list to be included in the Common
Effective Preferential Tariff (CEPT) scheme over the next five years.
     The CEPT is the vehicle for creating a free trade area within
the ASEAN region, home of the world's fastest growing economies.
     ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
     Throughout ASEAN, about 687 tariff lines will be lowered in
1996 and 2,496 others in the next four years.  Average tariff rates
will subsequently be brought down from 7.73% in 1996 to 4.03% by
2000 and 2.90% by 2003.
     ASEAN member economies vowed at the end of the fifth leaders'
summit in Bangkok on Dec. 15 to speed up the realization of an ASEAN
Free Trade Area even before the target date year of 2003 by
maximizing the number of items whose tariffs can be reduced to 0-5%
by the year 2000, as well as expanding the number of products whose
tariffs can be reduced to zero percent by the same year.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "18"></A>Copyright
ASIAN ECONOMIC NEWS via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Beijing public transport facing 300% fare hike+

BEIJING, Dec. 26 Kyodo

     Beijing subway riders will see a 300% rise in ticket prices
Jan. 1 as the municipal government aims to reduce rising public
transport subsidies and a heavily overburdened subway system, state
press reported Tuesday.
     Ticket prices will rise to 2 yuan (0.24 dollars) from the
present 0.5 yuan (0.06 dollars), while monthly passes will rise 120%
from the present 18 yuan (2.16 dollars) to 40 yuan (4.80 dollars),
the China Economic Times reported.
     The fare hikes are expected to help offset growing government
subsidies which amounted to 250 million yuan (30 million dollars) in
1994 and are expected to top 400 million yuan (48 million dollars)
for the current year, the paper said.
     Beijing's two-line 42-kilometer subway system has become
increasingly overcrowded as rapid urbanization has increased the
number of commuters and the growth in automobile traffic has snarled
the streets of the capital and rendered the once dependable public
bus system increasingly hit-and-miss.
     Bus tickets are expected to rise from an average 0.2 yuan to 0.5
yuan, it said.
     Last year, Beijing commuters made 530 million subway trips, and
the system's 180-people subway carriages were strained to as much as
50% beyond nominal capacity during peak hours, making travel
uncomfortable and dangerous.
     The Beijing government, fearful of worsening inflation, has
previously refused to approve the subway price hikes, leaving subway
managers no choice but to limit monthly passes and control ticket
sales during peak hours.



