Nissan to expand ties with S. Korea's Samsung Motor+

TOKYO, Dec. 28 Kyodo

     Nissan Motor Co. plans to exand its strategical ties with
Samsung Motor Inc. of South Korea to cover business cooperation in
the Asian market, officials of Japan's No. 2 automaker said Thursday.
     The proposed expansion calls for the partners to produce and
market passenger cars in each other's country, they said.
     Details of the business cooperation will be ironed out by the two
companies, they said.
     ''Cooperative relations will be strengthened to help Samsung
develop into a powerful friend,'' an executive of Nissan said.
     Possible capital cooperation is under study, said the
high-ranking official, who declined to be named.
     Under plans reviewed by Nissan, Pusan-headquartered Samsung will
market Nissan cars in South Korea under its own brand names while
Nissan will sell Samsung cars under the Nissan brand.
     Both partners will strengthen cooperation to produce cars
competitive in the respective countries, the officials said.
     The two companies will produce cars in Southeast Asia under a
burden-sharing scheme and cooperate in developing vehicles to boost
their productivity, they said.
     They also plan to standardize components and parts to be used
in their vehicles.
     Nissan has been providing technological assistance to Samsung
Motor in plant construction and production of components since April
last year.
     More than 100 Nissan officials now are assigned to assist the
South Korean automaker, which plans to start producing passenger cars
at a newly completed assembly plant in Pusan in January 1998, the
officials said.



