ASIAN ECONOMIC NEWS via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

4.3 mil. tourists visit Indonesia in '95+

JAKARTA, Dec. 28 Kyodo

     About 4.3 million foreign tourists visited Indonesia in 1995,
bringing in estimated revenues of 5.21 billion dollars, local
newspapers reported Thursday.
     ''The total number of foreign tourists entering Indonesia
through seven main gates as of December 1995 is estimated to have
reached 4.3 million,'' Tourism, Post and Telecommunications Minister
Joop Ave was quoted as saying Wednesday.
     Joop said the projected revenues represent an increase of 10.8%
from 4.7 billion dollars in 1994, though the number of tourist
arrivals rose only 7.3% from last year's level of slightly above
four million.
     According to a five-year development plan, the government
expected 4.5 million foreign tourists to visit Indonesia this year,
bringing revenues of at least 6 billion dollars.
     The number of tourist arrivals is projected to rise to between
five million and 5.4 million in 1996, bringing revenues of 6.91
billion dollars.
     Indonesia is targeting the tourist industry as a major foreign
exchange earner by 2005, when it expects to attract 11.1 million
visitors who will spend a total of 15 billion dollars in the country.
     The promotion of the country's tourist industry was hampered
early this year when the Japanese press reported that dozens of
Japanese tourists had become ill with cholera after returning from
the resort island of Bali.
     Japan, Singapore, Australia, Taiwan and Germany are major
sources of tourists for Indonesia.  In 1994 more than half of all
tourists, 56.83%, came from these five countries.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "29"></A>Copyright
ASIAN ECONOMIC NEWS via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

China aims to attract foreign investment in real estate+

BEIJING, Dec. 28 Kyodo

     China is trying to make its real estate sector more attractive
to foreigners, mainly in the area of low-cost, mass-market housing.
     There has been a boom in construction of office blocks, luxury
condominiums, villas and hotels in the past few years, mainly funded
by foreign investors seeking high profits through leasing or selling.
     But the government has now applied the brakes with a mixture of
the carrot and the stick to force foreign funds into sectors of
perceived greater need.
     It has issued new regulations lifting the previous exemption on
import duties and other taxes for materials and equipment brought in
from overseas for the construction of virtually any type of real
estate project.
     Currently, there are restrictions on the approval of land
available for such projects as well as a value-added tax for real
estate.
     A Circular on Strict Control of the Development of Luxury Real
Estate Projects was also introduced in late 1995 and the regulation
speaks for itself in indicating government determination to control
what it reckoned was the main reason the construction sector
overheated in the early 1990s, leading to runaway inflation.
     At the same time, foreign companies willing to cooperate with
the government in a massive urban renewal plan scheduled for the next
decade -- razing entire low-rise residential districts in many cities
and replacing them with high-rise apartment blocks -- will be given
preferential treatment as well as a guaranteed rate of return on
their investments.
     According to Minister of Construction Hou Jie, the government's
efforts to bring the real estate sector under tighter control are
beginning to pay off.
     In 1992, for example, investment in building construction
projects rose 117% over the previous year.  By 1994, growth had been
reduced to a 41.3%, and Hou anticipated an even lower increase this
year.
     ''There are four million urban families facing severe housing
problems.  The per capita urban housing space in at least half the
country is below the national average and 40 million square meters of
urban housing are dangerous and in urgent need of repair or
replacement,'' he said.
     Hou is trying to persuade potential foreign investors that the
development of low-cost housing, while yielding lower profits,
actually involves less risk and will represent the chief investment
trend in Chinese real estate in the foreseeable future.
     According to the minister, it takes one year to organize a
contract for a major hotel and at least three years to build it.  It
then takes eight or nine years to recover investments and reap
profits.
     On the other hand, the construction of an ordinary housing
project requires only six months for the entire cycle.  Two cycles
per year can be completed in south China but only one in north China
due to the inclement weather.
     ''The great demand for housing continues to offer foreign
investors excellent prospects for earning good returns.  Foreign
businesses investing in real estate can earn higher profits than the
current international level in developed countries,'' Hou said.
     ''Internationally, average profits for real estate range from 6
to 8%, with the rate in some countries dropping to 2%. In China,
average profit seldom falls below 30%,'' he said.
     Taking the lead in this area is the Shanghai municipal
government, which is counting on new preferential policies to help
overcome the resistance of foreign construction companies to becoming
involved in the city's ambitious urban housing redevelopment program.
     Guaranteed after-tax returns on investment will be limited to
15%, but the main sweetener is new policies designed to reduce the
risks and red tape involved in building cheap apartments for
residents forced out by urban projects.
     According to Huang Yuejing, deputy general secretary of the
Shanghai municipal government, regulations allowing foreign
investment in domestic housing projects were actually issued at the
end of 1993 but did not find any takers.
     ''Potential investors were discouraged by the huge outlays for
demolition of old buildings, relocation of residents and the
provision of utilities, all of which took a huge bite out of
prospective profits,'' he said.
     Foreign developers also had to team up with local parties to buy
a plot of land for redevelopment, and also pay a transfer fee for the
rights to the land, adding to the costs and risks.
     To overcome resistance, Huang said, ''We have come up with new
policies which we estimate will save overseas investors much of their
expense if they put their money into housing projects for domestic
sale rather than for overseas buyers.''
     The new approach, which applies to all foreign-invested projects
in areas with high concentrations of shabby or dangerous houses,
calls for the local authority to allocate the land to the Chinese
partner in a joint venture, with the foreign side providing the
financing.
     The Shanghai municipal government has pledged to buy the entire
housing project when completed and be responsible for its eventual
sale.  The profits reaped by the foreign investor can be remitted
overseas free of the normal restrictions on foreign exchange.
     The Shanghai approach is likely to be copied by other municipal
authorities.  Beijing, for example, is reported to be considering a
similar package of financial incentives with a guaranteed return of
18%.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "30"></A>Copyright
ASIAN ECONOMIC NEWS via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Cambodia counts on foreign funds for 45% of revenue+

PHNOM PENH, Dec. 28 Kyodo

     Cambodia still depends on foreign aid and borrowings from
multilateral aid institutions for 45.1% of its budgeted revenue for
fiscal 1996 which begins April, according to the state budget
approved Thursday by the National Assembly.
     The parliament endorsed the government's overall budget proposal
totaling 1.45 trillion riels (5.66 million dollars) for fiscal 1996.
     The budget size represented an increase of 13.2% over a year
earlier.
     Although the budgetary dependency on foreign money declined
from the preceding year's 45.9%, the rate is still alarmingly high,
analysts say.
     In breaking down the budgeted expenditures in percentage terms,
defense accounted for the biggest chunk at 34.9%, down from the
preceding year's 38.9%.
     The budget for the Interior Ministry ranked second at 15.2%,
down from the preceding year's 16.8%.
     These defense and security expenditures shrank somewhat as the
security threat from the Khmer Rouge guerrillas eased.
     The Cambodian government budgeted a 111% increase in
tourism-related expenditures, a 65% increase in welfare outlays and
a 36% raise for royal family-related outlays.



