ASIAN ECONOMIC NEWS via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Daiichi Pharmaceutical opens development unit in China+

TOKYO, Dec. 29 Kyodo

     Daiichi Pharmaceutical Co. has established a wholly owned
clinical drug development subsidiary in Beijing, a Daiichi spokesman
said Friday.
     The subsidiary will conduct clinical tests of new, promising
drugs concurrently in both Japan and China.
     The subsidiary will enable Daiichi to move quickly in new areas,
giving it an advantage over its competitors, the spokesman said.
     He said the new subsidiary, Daiichi Pharmaceutical (China) Co.,
is capitalized at 5 million dollars.
     It will start clinical tests of the synthetic antibacterial drug
Cravit and the cerebral neurotransmission improvement drug Translon
at a Beijing hospital from March, the spokesman said.  Tests of other
drugs will begin gradually.
     Daiichi expects to obtain Chinese government approval for Cravit
and Translon in 1998, he said.
     The subsidiary will then establish a joint production and sales
company for the drugs with a local pharmaceutical firm, and Daiichi
will invest some 3 billion yen on facility construction, the
spokesman said.
     Daiichi aims to raise its annual sales in China to 10 billion
yen by 2000, he said.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
