<A NAME = "32"></A>Copyright
ASIAN ECONOMIC NEWS via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Japan moves on economic sea zone could spark rows: paper+

TOKYO, Dec. 29 Kyodo

     The government is moving toward ratifying the international
ocean treaty and creating a 200-mile exclusive economic zone that
will likely inflame territorial disputes with China and South Korea,
the Tokyo Shimbun reported Friday.
     The daily said in a front-page article that the government hopes
to ratify the 1982 U.N. Convention on the Law of the Sea during the
upcoming regular Diet session and establish the exclusive economic
zone.
     The convention, which went into force in November last year,
obliges all signatories to recognize an exclusive 200-mile economic
zone off a nation's coasts.
     Within their zones, states have the exclusive right to fish or
to exploit natural resources such as oil, reclaim land or construct
artificial islands.
     In question will be Japan's dispute with China over the Senkaku
Islands, known in Chinese as the Diaoyutai Islands, in the East China
Sea.
     Tokyo also disputes South Korea's claim to Takeshima Island,
known as Tokto in Korea, in the Sea of Japan.
     The Senkaku Islands, located some 150 kilometers northeast of
the northern tip of Taiwan, are also claimed by Taipei.
     China has said it plans to ratify the sea convention next
summer.  South Korea has already ratified the treaty.
     Some Foreign Ministry officials said earlier this month Japan
should delineate a 200-mile zone with the Senkaku Islands as a
base of reference, arguing that refraining from doing so could be
interpreted by the Chinese as a lack of interest in the territory.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "33"></A>Copyright
ASIAN ECONOMIC NEWS via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Japanese help Indonesian village improve iron casting+

URAWA, Japan, Dec. 29 Kyodo

     The Japanese city of Kawaguchi in Saitama Prefecture, bordering
Tokyo, famous for its cast-iron pots and pans, is helping an
Indonesian village bring its metal-casting technology up to date by
introducing modern cupola furnaces.
     Six makers of cast-iron products in Kawaguchi have founded the
Kasia metal-casting technology exchange cooperative hoping to help
realize a model factory in Ceper, a village on Java, by the middle of
next year, said Kenichi Masuda, head of the cooperative.
     Because of the strong yen, the Kawaguchi makers have suffered
from sluggish demand, even for products made from new materials such
as ceramics.  They have embarked on the project in a bid to overcome
the mood of the recession, he said.
     The name ''Kasia'' is a contraction of Kawaguchi and Asia.
Ceper has some 300 metal casters who make their products in
hand-shaped sand molds.
     ''Their technological level equals that of Japan in the Edo
period (1615-1868), with rejects sometimes amounting to almost 80%
of production,'' Masuda said.
     The idea for the project was born when the head of a
metal-casting cooperative from Ceper requested technological
assistance after inspecting Masuda's factory during a visit to Japan
in 1991.
     The village is providing the site and the factory free of
charge.  Kawaguchi workers skilled in the latest metal-casting
techniques will serve as instructors at the Ceber model factory and
bring the know-how of some 20 local metalworkers up to date.
     Also planned are a library and a metal-casting contest.
     Indonesia relies heavily on imports for cast-iron products,
particularly machine parts.
     Japanese makers producing in Indonesia are not able to keep up
with demand.  Masuda, though, said he does not expect the model
factory to make profits right from the start.
     ''We are ready to live with a deficit in the first few years.
For us, the project is significant in giving new impetus to Japan's
metal-casting industry which is in a fix.''



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "34"></A>Copyright
ASIAN ECONOMIC NEWS via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Steelmakers face price-cut pressure for exports to Asia+

TOKYO, Dec. 29 Kyodo

     Japanese steelmakers are under growing pressure to cut prices
of Asia-bound steel products due to a glut in the market, steel
companies officials said Friday.
     They said China's restraint on economic expansion, including a
switch to a tight credit policy, is primarily responsible for the
glut.
     The Chinese government has ordered domestic steelmakers to limit
their production to reduce large inventories resulting from
overproduction in 1994, they said.
     China's crude steel output was estimated at 90 million tons in
1994.
     Japanese steel producers recently bowed to a Chinese demand for
a price cut of about 8.0% for their steel shipments in the
February-July period.
     The officials said Japanese steel companies already face growing
calls for price cuts from Thailand, Singapore and Malaysia.
     Prices of steel products bound for India and the Middle East
have also declined by about 10% from the July-September level of
this year.
     Trading houses said some Japanese steelmakers have offered
price cuts of up to 15% to secure export volume.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
