<A NAME = "12"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

HONG KONG: OPPORTUNITIES ARISE FROM CLK'S PRIVATE FACILITIES

Construction of the privately financed facilities at Chek Lap Kok,
including cargo handling and aircraft maintenance, got off to a flying
start with key awards for design work going mainly to British firms.
One of the biggest schemes is the $1bn construction of the world's
largest air cargo complex by Hong Kong Air Cargo Terminals. Work
involves a six-storey main building totalling 274,000 sq m and a 46,000
sq m two-storey express cargo centre.

The lead building consultant is Ove Arup who are working in tandem with
Foster Asia as the architectural sub-consultants. British Steel (Asia)
is to supply 53,550 tonnes of steel piles for foundations specialist
Franki Contractors, owned by Germany's Bilfinger & Berger. The main
construction is being done by Hong Kong's Gammon Construction, which is
jointly owned by Trafalgar House and Jardine Pacific.

Cathay Pacific Catering Services (CPCS) has chosen Scott Wilson
Kirkpatrick as the structural and civil consultants for its $200m in-
flight catering facility, one of three planned at the airport. Other
consultancy awards for the 56,000 sq m three-storey building include US
engineers, Parsons Brinckerhoff Asia who are acting as the mechanical
and electrical consultants and local firms Davis Langdon and Seah who
have been appointed as the quantity surveyors and Wong Tung & Partners
are the architects. The foundations will be undertaken by the local
firm, Shui On.

Six contractors - Dragages (French), Paul Y/Downer, Gammon, Hsin Chong,
Hip Hing and Shui On (all Hong Kong) - are having their bids for the
main building contract evaluated by the CPCS project team which hopes
to award the contract in January.

The facility is one of three in-flight kitchens planned at CLK. Others
will be build by LSG-Lufthansa Sky Chefs and Switzerland's Gate Gourmet
International, although consultants are only just being appointed.

The next key project is a $435m headquarters and hotel development for
Cathay Pacific Airways. The architects are Llewelyn-Davis with Harris
and Sutherland acting as structural consultants and Widnell as the
quantity surveyors. Bids for the foundations will be invited early next
year. The construction work, which has been split into four phases,
includes a 10-storey, 69,000 sq m reinforced concrete frame, glass
curtain wall clad office building and a 25-storey, 23,000 sq m, 500 bed
staff hotel.

Other private facilities include a second air cargo centre which is
planned by Asia Air Freight Terminals - a joint venture comprising
mainly Singaporean companies. The main consultants on the 22,000 sq m
scheme are Jones Lang Wootton Building Consultancy. The Hong Kong firm,
Liang Peddle Thorp are the architects, but the client has refused to
name the other firms involved. Piling contractors have just been asked
to prequalify.

There has been a reluctance by Hong Kong Aircraft Engineering, the
company undertaking aircraft maintenance, to name the professional team
who will advise on a massive hanger capable of handling three jumbo
jets side by side.

Other projects are far less advanced. These include the aviation fuel
system awarded to Aviation Fuel Supply which is led by Cathay Pacific
Airways, aircraft line maintenance which will be undertaken by Pan Asia
Pacific Aviation Services and China Aircraft Services, a 600-bed
airport hotel franchised to Regal Hotels, and a freight forwarding
centre being developed by Sun Hung Kai Properties.



