<HR>
<A NAME = "14"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

TAIWAN: SMALL PRINT LEADS TO TUNNEL CONTRACT TERMINATION

Accusations between Taiwan Ret-Ser Engineering and France's Spie
Battignolles TP (SB) threaten to further delay the completion of the
31km Taipei-Ilan Expressway. The dispute is a result of the termination
of a tunnelling contract between the two companies.

Touted as the 'key to the success of the project,' by the ministry of
transportation and communication's (MOTC) Taiwan Area National
Expressway Engineering Bureau (TANEEB), the 12.9km Pinglin Tunnel has
yet to be started. In a contract signed in October 1993, Ret-Ser sub-
contracted the building of the tunnel to SB. However, the contract
required Ret-Ser to build a 12.9km pilot tunnel. Although construction
on the pilot tunnel began in July 1991, only 1.5km was completed by the
proposed date of March 25, 1995.

'Poor geological conditions is the reason for the delay,' said Ret-
Ser's department of special projects director, Tsai Hsi-chi. He
explained that the $1m tunnel boring machine (TBM), used by Ret-Ser for
the first time, got stuck on numerous occasions, the most recent
incident halting work for a nine month stretch. In addition, water
inflow to the tunnel was more than triple the maximum safe operating
limit of 35 litres per second which halted work.

TANEEB has already approved a 300-day extension for Ret-Ser to complete
the pilot tunnel, but Ret-Ser is currently preparing more documents to
apply for a further 365 day extension in the near future, said Ret-Ser
executive vice president, Shen Ching-peng.

Despite the non-completion of the pilot tunnel Ret-Ser asked SB to
begin tunnelling on the main tunnel. SB refused claiming the work would
be a safety hazard and could result in unforeseen problems and delays
without all the geological data gleaned from the completion of the
pilot tunnel. SB project manager, Olivier Colin, likened the situation
to the construction of a house - the foundations must be completed
before construction can proceed. 'We proposed a number of alternative
construction methods for the main tunnel without geological data from
the pilot tunnel, but this was rejected by Ret-Ser,' he said.

The French sub-contractor has now filed a civil suit accusing Ret-Ser
of wrongful termination of the $50m contract after failing to re-
negotiate the price on the original contract. SB have asserted that Ret-
Ser's delay on the completion of the pilot tunnel has resulted in
increased cost and time, thus requiring a revised amount in the new
contract. SB claimed that it stated as a pre-condition in the Request
for Proposal three years ago that the quote on the tunnel project was
based on the completion of the pilot tunnel. Ret-Ser maintains that
there were no clauses in the contract that stated the pilot tunnel must
be completed before SB begins boring the main tunnel.

Ret-Ser's Tsai has also asserted that a change in identity of SB is the
main reason for terminating the contract. The original sub-contractor
was the 150-year-old Spie Battignolles that in July became 'Spie
Battignolles TP' after a restructure and recapitalisation in a merger
between Spie Battignolles and its parent company Schneider. 'According
to Taiwan law, the name on the contract cannot be changed. SB is not
the one who entered into the contract,' said Shen.

Ret-Ser further allege that SB provided inadequate documentation on the
'new company.' Ret-Ser says it is unable to ascertain that the new SB
meets the requirements under the Pre-Qualification list, a factor that
first won Spie Battignolles the contract. Further negotiations with
Schneider proved futile as the parent company refused to act as
guarantor for SB, said Shen.

According to Colin, SB is still the same company as the name on the
contract. The 'TP' or 'Civil Works' was added to the name to emphasise
its focus on civil construction, he said. SB's capital was boosted from
about $40m to around $161m after the merger with Schneider. 'SB's
recapitalisation made the company stronger. A change of name was just
an excuse from Ret-Ser to terminate the contract,' he added.

SB's official spokesperson, C. P. Chen, has said that another problem
behind the dispute is that many local companies still operate in the
'Chinese Way'. 'Political and cultural differences stand in the way of
productive co-operation between local and foreign companies,' he said.

An example of the 'Chinese Way' was Ret-Ser's forcible take-over of
SB's construction and office facilities in mid-November. SB
subsequently lodged a criminal complaint to the Ilan district
prosecutor's office which is currently investigating the case. 'It is
true that the three TBMs are the assets of TANEEB and Ret-Ser during
the construction, but checking SB employee's passports and confiscating
the company's accounts, geological data and documents is unreasonable
and illegal according to our lawyer,' said Chen. He agreed that SB was
in for a tough legal battle against the government-owned Ret-Ser,
technically a department under the Executive Yuan (Cabinet)'s
Vocational Assistance Commission for Retired Servicemen, rather than a
state-owned enterprise. 'But SB is willing to take on that challenge to
protect its own interest,' Chen added.

Colin sees the cause of the dispute as a simple case of shirking
responsibilities. 'The only reason Ret-Ser terminated the contract is
to hide the fact that they cannot finish the project and to escape
their responsibility. They desperately needed a scapegoat, and as it is
around election time, SB became that ideal scapegoat.'

However, Spie Battignolle has previously acted as the sub-contractor to
Ret-Ser for projects in Saudi Arabia, Indonesia and Bahrain which have
been successful according to Colin. 'SB had a good working relationship
and worked in total confidence with Ret-Ser - that is why we came over
to Taiwan. SB will work again in Taiwan if a new opportunity arises and
conditions are different. We will be more prudent, since we are not the
only company that have problems with government agencies. The
construction business can be bad and risky but not everything can be
100 per cent covered on paper. A lot of working relationship is based
on trust,' he said.

Meanwhile, Ret-Ser is in discussion with Italy's Torno about completing
the Pinglin Tunnel. The Italian construction company has already won a
bid to work on a 4.8km tunnel, also on the Taipei-Ilan Expressway.
Torno was one of the two companies that expressed interest in the
Pinglin Tunnel out of eight companies that put in a Request for
Proposal. Shen said that Ret-Ser will approach the remaining six
companies individually to find a new sub-contractor to finish the
project.



