<A NAME = "15"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

PHILIPPINES: BARRIERS ARE OVERCOME FOR LRT-3

One of Manila's light rail transit schemes has finally cleared
financial, political and legal barriers. It now seems that the project,
known as LRT-3, can go ahead unimpeded.

Senator Franciso Tatad and other opponents had tried to stop the
project, but the Supreme Court has thrown out their petition.

The concessionaires, led by Fil-Estate and Ayala have raised $150m as
initial paid-up capital. They have appointed JP Morgan as their
financial advisor, and are looking to raise a further $100m and to
float $300m worth of debt instruments on the international capital
markets. Domestic banks (local and foreign) have agreed to provide the
remaining $100m of the total $650m that is required.

The last problem was posed by the so-called 'Save Edsa Movement', led
by columnist Antonio Abaya and supported by the Philippine Motor
Association. Edsa is an acronym for the road along which LRT-3 will
run. The movement objected to the traffic chaos that will be created
when the work is undertaken. It initially proposed an alternative route
for LRT-3, along Circumferential Road No. 5, which runs parallel to
Edsa. However, it has softened its stance and is amendable to the route
along Edsa, as long as alternative routes are provided for vehicles
before construction commences.



