<A NAME = "16"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

INDONESIA: ELABORATE LRT PLANS ARE ANNOUNCED FOR JAKARTA

In the middle of December, 1995, PT Citra Lamtoro Gung Persada (CLGP)
suddenly announced an elaborate extension to its plans for a light rail
system in Jakarta. It has now said it will spend $1.2bn on a three-
level transport artery in Jakarta, comprised of a public road on the
ground, a light rail line above that and a toll road on the top. The
structure is to cover a distance of 16km between Bintaro in south
Jakarta, downtown Kota in north Jakarta, and a further 2km from Bintaro
to Blok M, also in south Jakarta.

Company chief executive, Bambang Soeroso, said that a consortium would
be formed in May 1996 to carry out the project and finance would be
arranged. CLGP spokesman, Fariza Irawadi, said that the light-rail
aspect of the venture was almost certain to require the participation
of one or more foreign partners. 'Up to now we haven't had any
experience in this country with light rail,' he told AIM. He added that
the company's considerable experience in elevated toll road
construction meant that overseas expertise was unlikely to be needed
for the remainder of the project. Fariza would not be drawn on the
composition of the consortium, but confirmed that several foreign
companies have expressed interest.

He said the plan had not yet been completed and that there might still
be further administrative 'input' on the scheme. 'After that the final
engineering design will be prepared. It will be finished in one year,
with construction beginning in 1997,' he said.

Only in November the plan was still known to the public as entailing
the construction of a light-rail simpliciter. At the beginning of
November, director general of highway construction, Soeharsono
Martakim, said that construction of the light rail line, at that time
still known as the Light Rapid Transit (LRT) system, would begin in
April 1996. In mid-November, when the project carried a price tag of
$800m, minister of transportation, Haryanto Dhanutirto, said that the
LRT would be carried out by CLGP in co-operation with Steady Safe, the
owner of a city taxi business.

The project outline has changed extensively, but what has stayed the
same is that it remains in the hands of CLGP which is controlled by the
president's daughter. The company remains the major private-sector
investor in Indonesian toll roads. It has also built tolls roads in
Malaysia and is preparing to undertake two large toll road projects in
the Philippines.

The Jakarta light rail project was awarded to CLGP early this year
without a tender. Commenting on the fact recently, Haryanto said it
followed because the project had been proposed to the government by the
company. In August, Ms Rukmana publicly denied that her company's
success in gaining infrastructure projects was related to her close
relationship with the president. 'My father, who happens to be trusted
by the people to lead the nation, has always reminded me not to use his
name for business purposes,' she told a local newspaper.

On December 16, 1995, CLGP's subsidiary, Citra Bhakti Margatama Persada
(CBMP) broke ground on the Cikunir-Cakung-Cilicing-Tanjung Priok
section of Jakarta's Outer Ring Road. The 1,920km section of toll road
is scheduled to be operational in 1999, at an investment of Rp1,040m
($4.5bn). Company representatives said the project would be financed
with loans from domestic banks. CBMP is a BOT joint venture between
state-owned toll road company Jasa Marga (34.83 per cent) and CLGP,
Tridan Satriaputra Indonesia, Bhaskara Duniajaya and Yayasan Tiara
Indah. Consultants on the project include Pacific Consultant
International and BIEC International.



