<A NAME = "17"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

BATAM AIRPORT IS UPGRADED TO RIVAL SINGAPORE

Indonesia has started construction of an aircraft maintenance facility
and upgraded the international airport on the island of Batam in a bid
to rival Singapore's Changi airport's role as an international flight
hub for the south-east Asian region. Batam island, which lies a few
kilometres south of Singapore, is being developed as an industrial and
tourist centre together with the Singapore government authorities. The
island's airport already serves as a centre for cargo traffic for
industrial estates located there.

Batam's Hang Nadim airport, controlled by the Indonesian government
through the Batam Industrial Development Authority, has had its runway
extended to 4km at a cost of about $217m. It can now accommodate wide-
bodied aircraft such as Boeing 747-400s.

Construction of an aircraft maintenance and services facility has also
started. PT BAM, or Batam Aircraft Maintenance, located adjacent to
Batam's airport, is scheduled to complete a hangar at a cost of Rp18bn
($7.9m) by the end of 1996. It is hoped that BAM's services will help
lure customers away from Singapore's Changi airport. The maintenance
facility is being built to handle different types of aircraft including
Boeing 737 jets, Fokker planes and Indonesian-built CN 235s. BAM is
majority-owned by Indonesian entities including the state-owned
aircraft manufacturing company, IPTN, and Sempati Air, a private
domestic airline controlled by one of President Suharto's sons.

However, Singapore Technologies Aerospace, a unit of the Singapore
government's Singapore Technologies, also has a 25 per cent stake in
BAM. Singapore Technologies Aerospace is originally believed to have
wanted to take a majority stake in the project, a move which was
opposed by Indonesia's minister for research and technology, Mr B.J.
Habibie. As chairman of the Batam Industrial Development Authority, Mr
Habibie is closely involved with the island's progress.

Batam's goal is to become an international aviation hub. Aviation fuel
is about 20 per cent less expensive on Batam than in Singapore.
However, Singapore's Changi airport controls flight information in
parts of Indonesian airspace, including Batam. The latter has been a
point of some friction between Indonesia and Singapore, although the
boundaries of flight information regions were revised in September 1995
when President Suharto made an official visit to Singapore.

Indonesia was given control of air traffic services over an additional
space stretching from south of its islands of Sumatra to the Natuna
islands in the South China Sea but Singapore's Changi airport retains
supervision of aircraft movements from airports in Batam and
neighbouring Bintan.

The Indonesian authorities want Batam's Hang Nadim airport to act as a
transit and connecting point for international flights. However,
Indonesian officials admit this is still a long way off. 'It is still
hard for international air carriers to transit at Hang Nadim, as the
flow of goods and passengers is still low,' the director general of air
transportation, Mr Zainuddin Sikado, was quoted as saying in the
Jakarta Post. 'The most important thing will be how Batam improves the
quality of its services.'

Currently, there are no international flights to Batam, although eleven
domestic flights connect Batam to other airports throughout the
Indonesian archipelago. Local press reports said that by the end of
1999 twelve additional domestic routes are due to be served from Hang
Nadim.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "18"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

SINGAPORE DECIDES TO LIST INFRASTRUCTURE PROJECTS

Singapore's finance minister, Dr Richard Hu, has just announced the
creation of a foreign board for listing regional infrastructure
projects on the Stock Exchange of Singapore (SES). The listing criteria
of the foreign board are less stringent than those for the main board.
Infrastructure projects do not require a profit record, they need only
show potential for a reasonable rate of return and good cash flow
'vouched by competent and independent experts.'

For analysts the comparisons with Malaysia are unavoidable. In
September, the Securities Commission there issued a set of
comprehensive guidelines that paved the way for infrastructure projects
to be listed on the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE). Unlike
conventional initial public offerings, the guidelines stated that
infrastructure project companies (IPCs), which have long gestation
periods, can offer their shares based on forecast earnings, even if
they do not have a profit record.

Candidates for a listing on the KLSE are likely to include Ekran
Corporation's M$15bn ($5.9bn) Bakun hydroelectric project in Sarawak
and the five independent producers. More recently, Malaysia's finance
minister, Anwar Ibrahim, said Malaysia may allow foreign infrastructure
companies controlled by Malaysians to list their shares on the KLSE.

The Singapore guidelines state that infrastructure companies wishing to
list on the proposed new foreign board must have secured projects worth
at least S$300m ($212m). These projects must have a remaining lifespan
of at least 15 years from the date of listing, though companies with
concessions of at least 10 years will also be considered.

'Companies engaged in infrastructure projects need not show profits in
the financial year before listing, nor any record of prior profits, but
they must demonstrate strong cash-flow and a good rate of return over
the duration of the concession,' the SES said in a statement last week.
By comparison, Singapore-incorporated non-infrastructure companies must
have a paid-up capital of S$15m ($10.6m) and cumulative pre-tax profit
of at least S$7.5m ($5.3m) for the last two years, of which S$3m must
be chalked up in the latest year prior to listing. Alternatively, these
companies can be considered if they show a pre-tax profit of at least
S$10m ($7.1m) for the latest year.

'As companies listed on the foreign board are expected to have shorter
track records, investment in these securities may entail additional
risk,' the SES said. 'Warning about the risks specific to such
companies will be required and such warning must be prominently
displayed on the front cover of the prospectus.'

The shares of these companies will be quoted in a foreign currency and
traded in minimum board lot sizes of $2000 or the equivalent. The SES
has also introduced a moratorium requiring company owners to hold their
shareholding for a year after listing. Although they can sell some of
their stake in the subsequent two years, they must hold at least 51 per
cent of the total shares that they had at the time of the listing.

'At least one promoter holding at least 20 per cent of the pre-
floatation issued capital must have the relevant technical management
expertise to carry out and operate the project successfully and to
fulfil all requirements of the project,' the SES said. Companies listed
on the foreign board can transfer to the main board after one year.
However, they have to meet the latter's more stringent listing
criteria. Analysts have welcomed the establishment of the new board,
the third on the local bourse. They say the new board will help raise
the stature of Singapore as a leading regional financial centre.

One investment banker said, 'the new board could attract to Singapore
many large regional companies which are currently contemplating raising
capital in Hong Kong, Tokyo and Sydney,' he said. 'However the shares
of companies listing on the foreign board are expected to be targeted
mainly at institutional buyers'.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "19"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

THAILAND: BTS MASS TRANSIT OWNERSHIP IS RESTRUCTURED

Tanayong, the concessionaire for Bangkok's elevated rail transit, will
issue $160m worth of secured bonds as part of a shareholder
restructuring, as doubts continue to grow over its financial status.
The listed real estate firm reported in a mandatory stock market filing
that details of the issue price, collateral and launch time would be
released at a later date.

Talks have also opened with Thai-based Siam Commercial Bank on a
planned mobilisation of $562m from local capital markets, which will
form the core of financing for the $1.7bn project. It has already
secured a $50m loan from the International Finance Corporation and
hopes to raise a further $424m from KFW of Germany. 'We understand
contracts for the loans will be signed around the end of the year
(1995) and payment will be made in full to contractors shortly
afterwards,' said a banking executive.

Piling work on the 24km Bangkok Transit System railway began a year ago
but Tanayong has yet to come up with a funding package. Primarily a
developer of low-cost housing estates, it has been heavily affected by
a downturn in the property market and is regarded as having virtually a
zero credit rating. Bangkok Bank resigned as financial adviser earlier
this year after declining to guarantee a loans package. Its
replacement, Siam Commercial Bank, is insisting on a shareholder
restructuring that will bring in equipment suppliers and contractors on
an equity basis.

Italian-Thai Development, the sole construction contractor, has not
been paid since work started, and is expected to hold a 10 to 15 per
cent stake. 'The construction cost of the BTS skytrain is around Bt4m-
Bt5m ($160,000-$200,000) a month. We have received only Bt200m ($8m)
from Tanayong, while the value of work completed is around Bt1.86bn
($74.4m),' said company president, Premchai Karnsauta.

Siemens, the main equipment supplier, and Siam Commercial are expected
to be the other shareholders. Tanayong has agreed to reduce its stake
to 60 per cent, after attempts to push it into a minority role were
thwarted by contractual obligations. This will block efforts to raise
cash by listing the project on the stock exchange, as market rules
require a larger public shareholding. However, another attempt will be
made to diminish Tanayong's stake when its four-year concession
expires.

A Siam Commercial spokesman confirmed that 10 financial institutions
had been approached to join the domestic loans deal, which the bank
will guarantee in the absence of security from Tanayong. The local
package replaced earlier plans for an issue of US Yankee bonds that was
scuttled by bank worries over foreign exchange fluctuations.

Any further delays in putting together a loans package will almost
certainly force a halt in work on the mass transit, which depends
heavily upon the patience of Italian-Thai. About 12 per cent of the
piling work has been finished. 'We will continue to do advance work for
BTS in the next year. That is, we will wait until BTS is ready to pay,'
said Premchai, 'obviously Italian-Thai cannot be expected to continue
on the present basis.' The construction firm is issuing Bt4.9bn ($196m)
worth of bonds to pay for its shares acquisition.



