ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

CATHAY PACIFIC WITHDRAWS FROM AIRPORT JV

Cathay Pacific Airways has withdrawn from a Yn1.2bn ($144m) joint
venture to expand Xiamen airport in Fujian province. The project was
announced in August 1994 and involved expanding the aircraft apron area
and the airport's runway by 760m to 3.4km. However, Cathay's withdrawal
follows a series of setbacks which it claims have rendered the project
commercially unviable. Cathay, which owned 33 per cent of the project,
has said that it could not agree terms with Xiamen International
Airport, its mainland partner which holds the remaining 67 per cent. In
addition the Chinese authorities refused Cathay permission to run
airport security or ticketing sales, and wanted the time frame to be
less than 30 years. Cathay has invested no money in the project and a
spokesman for the company said that it would keep its options open for
other mainland airport investments.



